body:
It seems return a reference to captured variable that's moved into a closure is disallowed, no matter the closure is a `Fn`, `FnMut`,or `FnOnce`. But the compiler gives different error for `Fn`, `FnMut`, and `FnOnce`(You can uncomment the code in `main` to see it), which is confusing. If it's not allowed anyway, give a error that states "return a reference to captured variable that's moved into the closure is disallowed" should be more helpful.
```
fn main() {
    let _name = "name".to_string();
    let mut _foo = 10;
    let bar = 20;

    let _ = move ||  {
        // Uncomment the following line to turn this into a FnOnce
        // drop(_name);
        // Uncomment the following line to turn this into a FnMut
        // _foo += 1;
        &bar
    };
```
```
error: lifetime may not live long enough
  --> src/bin/clo.rs:12:9
   |
7  |     let _ = move ||  {
   |             -------
   |             |     |
   |             |     return type of closure is &'2 i32
   |             lifetime `'1` represents this closure's body
...
12 |         &bar
   |         ^^^^ returning this value requires that `'1` must outlive `'2`
   |
   = note: closure implements `Fn`, so references to captured variables can't escape the closure
```
